Here's a simple example of a C++ program that reads binary data from a file and displays it on the console. This program reads the binary data in chunks of 4 bytes, which is enough to store a 32-byte integer.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <cstdlib>
#include <cstring>

const int CHUNK_SIZE = 4;

void displayBinaryData(const char* data, int size) {
 for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {
 int value = (data[i] << 24 * i + 24 * (i - 1) + 16 +
 (data[i - 1] << 8) +
 (data[i - 2] << 16) +
 (data[i - 3] >> 8);
 std::cout << value << " ";
}
 std::cout << std::endl;
}

int main() {
 std::ifstream file("data.bin", std::ios::in | std::ios::binary);
 if (!file) {
 std::cerr << "Error opening file: " << strerror(errno) << std::endl;
 return 1;
}

char buffer[CHUNK_SIZE];
while (file.read(buffer, CHUNK_SIZE)) {
 displayBinaryData(buffer, CHUNK_SIZE);
}

if (file) file.close();
return 0;
}
```

This program uses a helper function `displayBinaryData` to convert the binary data into human-readable format. The main function opens the binary file in binary mode, reads it in chunks of 4 bytes, and calls `displayBinaryData` to display the data. The program also handles errors that may occur when opening the file and reads the data.

